    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-03-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-03-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="808"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d808">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">357.AB/3–2254</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by the Secretary of
                        State’s Special Assistant</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_ORL1">
                        <hi rend="italic">O’Connor</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d808fn1">Sent to <gloss target="#t_UNA1"
                            >UNA</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-03-22">March 22,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>American neutral observers in Kashmir</item>
                </list>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_LHC1">Lodge</persName> telephoned the Secretary
                    on March 20 in reference to the American neutral observers in Kashmir. <persName
                        corresp="#p_LHC1">Lodge</persName> says that <persName corresp="#p_MVKK1"
                        >Menon</persName> is genuinely and personally disturbed by the presence of
                    these observers and said that it was <persName corresp="#p_MVKK1"
                        >Menon</persName>’s view that the observers would never be accepted by India
                    anywhere and that their presence inevitably means trouble. <persName
                        corresp="#p_LHC1">Lodge</persName> added that a final decision was up to the
                    Secretary General rather than us but that the <gloss target="#t_SYG1"
                        >SYG</gloss> would be certainly influenced by what we had to say. <persName
                        corresp="#p_LHC1">Lodge</persName> felt that if we could concede this point,
                    we would improve our position with <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName>,
                    and it was his (<persName corresp="#p_LHC1">Lodge</persName>’s) recommendation
                    that we take the people out.</p>
                <p>The Secretary promised that he would look into the matter right away. I would
                    like to have your coordinated recommendation for the Secretary as soon as
                    possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ORL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">R. L. O’Connor</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
